Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Toss @butternut squash{8%ounce} on a
#baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @olive oil{1%tablespoon} and a pinch of @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Roast in oven until tender and lightly browned, ~{25-30%minutes}.

Meanwhile, bring @veggie stock concentrate{2} and 4 cups @water{4%cups} to a gentle simmer
in a #medium pot{} over low heat. Mince or grate @garlic{2%clove}. Halve, peel, and
finely chop @shallot{1}.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium heat. Add garlic and shallot and
cook, stirring, until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper. Add
@arborio rice{3/4%cup} to pan and toss until grains are translucent, ~{1-2%minutes}. Reduce
heat to medium low.

Add stock to pan ½ cup at a time, stirring after each addition. Allow rice to absorb stock
before adding more. Continue until rice is al dente, ~{25-30%minutes}—risotto should be
thick but not stiff and grains should have a little bite to them.

While risotto cooks, pick sage leaves from stems; discard stems. Set aside a few small
leaves for garnish, then finely chop the rest @sage{1/4%ounce}.

> Practice this Italian phrase while you wait for the risotto to finish:
> "Chi se move mangia e chi sta fermo secca." (Those who move eat. Those who stay still
> dry up.)

When risotto is done simmering, stir squash, chopped sage, @parmesan cheese{1/4%cup}(shredded),
and @butter{1%tablespoon} into pan. Season generously with salt and pepper. Divide between
plates. Garnish with @pepitas{1%ounce} and reserved sage leaves.